Geographically weighted regression (GWR)¶

Now that we have established that there are geographical patterns to the afgifte data (see afgifte_esda), the next step is to ask why these patterns exist. We can do this with generalized linear regression (GLR) and geographically weighted regression (GWR).

Generalized linear regression (GLR) explains how independent variables (e.g. average income, proximity to infrastructure, land value) affect a dependent variable (in our case, log(kg) of secondary resources received per postcode) using a formula. The formula describes whether the independent variables are correlated to the dependent variable, and how. Geographically weighted regression (GWR) is similar to linear regression, but instead of having one formula describing the entire dataset, you have one formula for each postcode (so that's 4000 formulas describing 4000 postcodes), describing relationships between variables within its neighborhood. This allows us to find out how strongly variables affect postcodes in different areas.

In this notebook, I would like to make a first attempt at conducting GWR analysis on the afgifte dataset. The dependent variable will be log(kg) of secondary resources received for each pc4 postcode area, and the indenpendent variables will come from the CBS dataset, and include variales like average land value, income, population, proximity to universities...etc. I don't expect to get an accurate model, or any significant results (I need more independent variable for that), but at least I can get a first understanding of how we would conduct GWR on our dataset.

This notebook will be separated into four parts: importing our independent variable from CBS data, generalized linear regression, geographically weighted regression, and exploring local bivariate relationships.

Exploratory regression¶

Before doing a regression analysis, we need to choose the right explanatory variables. In other words, we need to choose variables that will more likely have a significant effect on our dependent variable, log(kg). We can choose variables by reading existing literature (we've made a start with our previous paper), but we can also do this using tools. One of these tools is the exploratory regression tool developed by ArcGIS. This tool finds a combination of explanatory variables that best explains the dependent variable. It does this by first finding the best variable, then the best combination of two variables, then three variables...and so on, until a passing model is found. Each iteration is evaluated using a number a statistical tests - AICc, VIF, JB, and R2.

Explanation of the statistical tests:

  • Akaike information criterion (AIC): The Akaike information criterion (AIC) is an estimator of prediction error and thereby relative quality of statistical models for a given set of data. Given a collection of models for the data, AIC estimates the quality of each model, relative to each of the other models. Thus, AIC provides a means for model selection. The lower the number, the better the model.
  • Variance inflation factor (VIF): The Variation inflation factor (VIF) checks for redundant variables in a regression model. In other words, it checks if multiple variables have the same effect on the model. As a rule of thumb, a model with a VIF of 7.5 or lower is considered acceptable.
  • Jarque-Bera test (JB): The Jarque-Bera test checks whether data is normally distributed (follows a bell-shape curve). For exploratory regression, this test is applied to the errors of a model to see if errors are normally distributed. If the JB is far from zero, it signals that the errors are not normally distributed, and that the model is inaccurate.
  • Coefficient of determination (R2, pronounced R-squared): The coefficient of determination (usually called r-squared) shows how accurate a model is, or in other words, how well the formula explains the data. The r2 number can be interpreted as a percentage - for example, a model with an r2 of 0.86 explains 86% of data variability. As a rule of thumb, models with an r2 > 0.8 are deemed as passing.

Generalized linear regression¶

Generalized linear regression (GLR) explains how independent variables (e.g. average income, proximity to infrastructure, land value) affect a dependent variable (in our case, log(kg) of secondary resources received per postcode) using a formula (also called a model). The model describes whether the independent variables are correlated to the dependent variable, and how. The accuracy of the model can be checked with the following methods:

  • check if errors are spatially clustered (check visually, then spatial auto-correlation (global moran's I))
  • check if errors are normall distributed using Jarque-Bera statistic (not significant)
  • check for redundant variables with variable inflation factor (< 7.5, lower the better)
  • when comparing models: Akaike's Information Criterion (AICc), lower the better
  • check adjusted r2, higher the better (e.g. 0.86 = model explains 86% of data variability)

Using the mgwr tool created by Arizona State University (recommended by Bardia), we created a GLR model for our data. You can see a summary below.

Interpreting the GLR summary above

  • This GLR model has an R2 of 0.089, which means that it explains only 8.9% of the data variability - no where near the 80% we're looking for! This is expected - I haven't put in all explanatory variables yet, and the dependent variable log(kg) doesn't take into account the fact that there are multiple secondary resource types. It's also worth knowing that in social sciences papers, an R2 of 0.45 or above for GLR is already deemed acceptable.
  • The adjusted R2 (Adj. R2) is similar to the R2, but gives a penalty if you use too many explanatory variables to explain the model.
  • For the p-values of the variables, we are looking for values that are lower than 0.05, which means that there's only a 5% chance that the coefficient for this variable (Est.) could be generated by a random values. If the R2 was higher, the significant variables would be number of households (numHh), average household size (avHhSize), number of dwellings (numDwellings), kmMainRoad, kmMainTrain, kmTrain, kmHavo, 10kmHavo, and kmVmbo. However we shouldn't get too excited because our R2 is too low, so our model is inaccurate anyway.
  • Finally, the coefficients (shown as 'Est.' for parameter estimates) shows the correlation between the explanatory variables and the dependent variable log(kg). The bigger the number, the bigger the effect; a positive number means a positive correlation (i.e. more dwellings = less log(kg)); a negative numbers means negative correlation (i.e. less numHh = more log(kg)).

Geographically weighted regression¶

While generalized linear regression (GLR) explains the relationship between a dependent variable (log(kg)) and explanatory variables using one formula for the whole dataset (in our case, the whole of the Netherlands), geographically weighted regression does the same by using one formula for every single datapoint (in our case, that's every single postcode area). This means that, with gwr, we get 4000 formulas (aka models) for 4000 postcodes. How is this done?

  • First, the tool defines the 'bandwidth', which is the size of a 'neighborhood'. Here, we are asking the question, at which spatial scale do our explanatory variables affect the log(kg)? Do these processes happen at a national, provincial, municipal, or neighborhood scale? GWR assumes that all explanatory variables function at the same scale. The bandwidth can be defined using an algorithm called the 'golden section', which basically ping-pongs between random numbers until it finds the bandwidth that produces the model with the best AICc score.
  • Once the bandwidth is defined, the tool calculates a formula for each postcode. Let's say the bandwidth is a radius of 10km. This is what the tool does:
    • find all postcodes within a 10km radius of postcode A - this is the local neighborhood of postcode A (local neighborhood A).
    • calculate a formula that describes the relationship between the variables in local neighborhood A.
    • attribute that formula to postcode A.
    • this process is repeated for postcode B, C, D...until all 4000 postcodes have gone through it.

The result of the gwr is 4000 formulas that describe the local condition of 4000 postcodes. But why is this necessary? Why not just use one formula to describe the whole of the Netherlands using GLR? What GWR can tell us (and GLR can't) is how strongly an explanatory variable affects the dependent variable in different geographical areas of the dataset. For example, the number of households may have a bigger effect on log(kg) in the north of the Netherlands than the south.

GWR was conducted using the MGWR tool (using its GUI instead of code directly), and resulted in a summary txt file and detailed csv file, which shows the results of the GWR. A summary of the GWR results can be seen below.

Interpretation of GWR summary above:

  • The GWR model has an adjusted R2 (Adj R2) of 0.174. This means our model explains 17% of the data variability. Again, this is nowhere near 0.8 (80%), but it's higher than the GLR model from our previous step, which was 0.086 (8.6%).

For GWR, instead of having one coefficient for each explanatory variable, we have 4000 coefficients for each explanatory variable describing 4000 local neighborhoods of 4000 postcodes. The 'mean' column shows the average of the 4000 coefficients for each variable.
  • The GWR model has an adjusted critical t value of 2.887. This means that coefficients (or parameter estimates) with t-values that are between -2.887 and 2.887 are probably insignificant, just noise.

Diving deeper...¶

We can dive deeper into the GWR results by studying the resulting csv file. The csv file has the following columns that are relevant to us:

  • ols_residual - Residuals (error) from OLS model for every location point
  • gwr_yhat - yhat from MGWR for each location point
  • gwr_residual - Residuals (error) from MGWR for every location point
  • localR2 - Explained variation at each location point
  • beta_ - Columns starting with beta are parameter estimates for the covariates )
  • se_ - Columns starting with se are standard errors for estimates for the covariates
  • t_ - Columns starting with t are t values for estimates for the covariates
  • p_ - Columns starting with p are p values for estimates for the covariates
  • sumW_ - Sum of weights for the covariates at each location

Interpretation of map above:

  • local R2: In GWR, each postcode has its own model and its own R2, which shows how accurate the model is. The darker areas on the map (near Amsterdam, Lelystad) have higher local R2 values. This means that, in these areas, our explanatory variables can more accurately explain our dependent variable, log(kg). Note that even the most accurate models have a local R2 of 0.3, which is pretty far from 0.8.
  • best coefficient: This map shows the variable that best explains (or can best predict) log(kg) for each postcode. For example, in the pink areas on the map (in the N, SE, and SW tips of the country), log(kg) can be best explained by km_train. In other words, in the pink areas, the variable with the highest p-value is km_train.

Disclaimer: as of 22-April-2021, these are not publishable results, because the gwr model we created is highly inaccurate. These maps and their explanations only show what results and interpretations to expect when we input a more refined dataset in the upcoming weeks.

Local bivariate relationships¶

From the GWR results, we can also understand how a coefficient of one variable changes aross the country. This allows us to understand how the influence of each explanatory variable on the dependent variable changes across space. For example, the number of households could have a stronger influence on log(kg) in the north of the country, while a weaker influence on the south. Sometimes, the coefficient can even have different signs - postive in some areas, while negative in others. The maps below show the value of coefficients for numDwellings, kmMainRoad, and 10kmHavo for each postcode.

  • beta_numDwellings: This map shows the coefficients of numDwellings for each postcode, and therefore shows how strongly the number of dwellings have an effect on log(kg). The darker the area, the stronger the effect. If this gwr model was accurate (which it is not), I would say that, in the west of Friesland (the dark area), the number of dwellings seems to have a particular strong effect on log(kg) received.
  • beta_kmMainRoad: This map shows the coefficients of kmMainRoad for each postcode, and therefore shows how strongly the distance from the nearest main road has an effect on log(kg). This map has both positive and negative coefficients, meaning that, the number of kms from a main road leads to an increase in log(kg) in some areas, and a decrease in others. For example, around Groningen, the further a postcode is from the main road, the higher the log(kg); but around Amsterdam, the further a postcode is to a main road, the lower log(kg).
  • beta_10kmHavo: This map shows the coefficients of 10kmHavo for each postcode, and therefore shows how strongly the number of universities within a 10km radius has an effect on log(kg). In the red areas, more universities means higher log(kg); while in the blue areas, more universities means lower log(kg).

Statistically significant local bivariate relationships¶

A caveat of the maps above show the coefficients of all postcodes, even if those coefficients are not statistically significant. If we interpret these maps, we could end up identifying relationships that were merely caused by statistical noise. To ensure that our interpretation is accurate, we should filter out all coefficients that are insignificant. We do this by looking again at the critical t-value from the gwr results summary: 2.887. So for us, we should only be mapping postcodes with coefficients with a t-value that are either > 2.887 or < -2.887.

We will first try this out for beta_numDwellings. We we're trying to do here is to select coefficients (beta_numDwellings) that have a t-value (t_numDwellings) that are either > 2.887 or < -2.887.

# set critical t-value (see gwr summary.txt)
t = 2.887

# extract significant beta_numDwellings
def sig(row): 
    if row.t_numDwellings > t or row.t_numDwellings < -t: 
        return row.beta_numDwellings
    else: 
        return 0
results['sig_beta_numDwellings'] = results.apply(lambda row: sig(row), axis=1)
numSig = len(results[results.sig_beta_numDwellings > 0])

# plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(20,10))

# beta_numDwellings

ax[0].axis('off')
ax[0].set_title('beta_numDwellings')

results.plot(column='sig_beta_numDwellings', ax=ax[1], cmap='OrRd', legend=True)
ax[1].axis('off')
ax[1].set_title('sig_beta_numDwellings')

# display 
print('percentage of postcodes with significant results: {}'.format(round(numSig / len(results) * 100,2)))
plt.show()

# set critical t-value (see gwr summary.txt)
t = 2.887
t_ = ['t_numDwellings', 't_kmMainRoad', 't_10kmHavo']
b_ = ['beta_numDwellings', 'beta_kmMainRoad', 'beta_10kmHavo']
sb_ = ['sig_beta_numDwellings', 'sig_beta_kmMainRoad', 'sig_beta_10kmHavo']

for i in range(3): 
    def sig(row): 
        if row[t_[i]] > t or row[t_[i]] < -t: 
            return row[b_[i]]
        else: 
            return 0 
    results[sb_[i]] = results.apply(lambda row: sig(row), axis=1)
    numSig = len(results[results[sb_[i]] > 0])
    print('percentage of postcodes with significant results for {}: {}'.format(b_[i], round(numSig / len(results) * 100,2)))
